</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ugoladus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Poobah Goladus</span><br>  Posts: 2280<br> <font color=#333333>(9/23/02 1:11:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm46.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: PoP counter-proposal based on simple principles</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Further, while magicians complain about enchanter nukes encroaching on mage territory, wizards are complaining that mage nukes are now encroaching on wizard territory, using similar reasoning.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->True, and maybe this is off-the-wall unreasonable thinking but it's my opinion that all this worry about inter-class balance is out of place, at the very least until we can actually play the new expansion.<br>
<br>
Here's why I think the new nukes are fine for mages, at least for the moment:<br>
<br>
Mages have always had 3 main types of single target nukes.  Conjuration Shocks(magic), Evocation Shocks(fire), and Evocation Bolts(fire).<br>
<br>
The bolts have typically been the most powerful spells number-wise, but their utility is more limited than a normal nuke because they can be blocked by objects, the ground, a wall, or most frequently another player.  Bolts have also typically been Evocation-based, so for a mage to take full advantage of their relative power he must sacrifice some Conjuration ability.  As a partial compensation, bolts also have a nice long range.<br>
<br>
So.. I think bolts are balanced when they have a bit more power for their cost(level/mana/cast time/aggro/rarity/difficulty) than other mage nukes, so long as they are evocation based.  <br>
<br>
Firebolt of Tallon seems to fit this description exactly.  It is a fire based, evocation bolt with a good DPS and mana effeciency ratio.  It's the lowest level spell of the new nukes.<br>
<br>
I always thought of the Conjuration Shocks as the work horse nuke for mages.  They are solid and dependable magic-based nukes.   They aren't bolts, there are no recast times to fuss around with, and they are conjuration-based nukes.  These tend to have average or better than average ratio and dps relative to other mage spells.  Additionally, for a mage specialized in conjuration, the Conjuration Shocks are typically the most mana effecient spell of the tier.<br>
<br>
Black Steel seems to fit this description quite well.  It is a clear upgrade to Shock of Steel.  It has a large increase in mana effeciency, and a fair increase in dps.  Black Steel appears to be the clear choice for a Spec: Conjure magician who is interested in conserving mana while dealing good damage.<br>
<br>
To me, the Evocation Shocks are the fire-based alternative to the Conjure Shocks.  They had similar features but were Evocation based.  A mage not specialized in Conjure would probably find these preferable to the magic shocks for everyday use, and even a Conjure mage would utilize the fire-based nukes when resistances encouraged it.  Evoc shocks changed a little with Kunark.  The only real Evoc Fire Shock was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Char</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which featured a low cast time, med-low damage, and average mana effeciency.  It seems to me that the implentation of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Char</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was an attempt to distinguish the Evocation Fire Shocks from the Conjuration Shocks, and in my opinion it worked well.  I think Char is a great spell.<br>
<br>
I do not see an Evoc Shock with Planes of Power..  That seems like a hole to me, but I believe that is because of the new conjuration nuke with luclin, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  This new spell was unlike anything mages had before, an conjuration based fire nuke.  Except for over a short period of time (when Char or Scars is superior), SoFB had the best dps and best mana effeciency of any nuke in the mage aresnal.  Basically, rare is the situation where a level 60 magician will want to use a nuke other than SoFB.  To me, this is somewhat unfortunate and takes away a little of the skill needed to play a magician well.<br>
<br>
There is no direct upgrade to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in Planes of Power.  Instead, they have planned <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Sun Vortex</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which is a fire-based conjuration nuke but unlike SoFB is not superior in every way.  Even so, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Sun Vortex</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a clear and significant upgrade to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  That it doesn't appear to be the no-brainer best nuke at level 65 does not concern me much.  For a truely superior nuke, get the ancient spell.<br>
<br>
I think that the ratios on Firebolt, Black Steel, and Insanity could be toned down a tad to make wizards feel better, but otherwise our nukes look quite appropriate.  The only thing I find lacking is a real upgrade to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Char</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
